+# Security False-Positive Analysis — CVE-2026-32739 (libheif, Debian bookworm)
+
+**CVE-2026-32739** — *not-affected (false positive)*
+
+> This is a companion issue to CVE-2026-32738 (above). It lives in the **same HEIF
+> image-sequence / track parsing subsystem** and has the **same root cause and the same
+> `not-affected` verdict** for bookworm.
+
+| Field | Value |
+|-------|-------|
+| CVE | CVE-2026-32739 |
+| Package | `libheif` |
+| Distribution | Debian 12 (bookworm) |
+| Shipped version | `1.15.1` (`1.15.1-1+deb12uX`) |
+| Verdict | **not-affected** — vulnerable code not present |
+| Reason class | Feature introduced after the shipped version |
+
+---
+
+## 1. Summary
+
+CVE-2026-32739 reports a denial-of-service (infinite loop) issue in libheif's **HEIF
+image-sequence / track parsing** subsystem. The advisory states it affects *"versions
+1.21.2 and below"* and is fixed in `1.22.0`.
+
+Debian bookworm ships **libheif 1.15.1**. The vulnerable code — the `stts`
+(decoding-time-to-sample) box parser and its `Box_stts::get_sample_duration()` method —
+**does not exist in 1.15.1**. As with CVE-2026-32738, the entire ISOBMFF movie/track
+reading subsystem was added to libheif *after* the bookworm release.
+
+The "1.21.2 and below" wording is **numerically true but misleading**: `1.15.1 < 1.21.2`,
+yet the loop the exploit depends on is absent. A crafted "HEIF sequence file" cannot reach
+the vulnerable logic in 1.15.1 — the `stts` box is treated as an unknown box and skipped.
+
+**Conclusion: CVE-2026-32739 is a false positive for bookworm and should be marked
+`not-affected`.**
+
+---
+
+## 2. What the CVE describes
+
+> In versions 1.21.2 and below, a crafted 800-byte HEIF sequence file causes an infinite
+> loop in `Box_stts::get_sample_duration()`, consuming 100% CPU indefinitely with zero
+> progress, leading to DoS. The loop has no iteration limit or timeout and is triggered
+> during file open (parsing) — before any user interaction or image decoding. The process
+> stays alive (no crash, no error logged), making it invisible to crash-based monitoring.
+> This issue has been fixed in version 1.22.0.
+
+---
+
+## 3. Why this cannot occur in bookworm (1.15.1)
+
+`Box_stts` (the *decoding-time-to-sample* box) and its `get_sample_duration()` method are
+part of the same track-reading machinery as the `stsc`/`Chunk` code from CVE-2026-32738.
+The vulnerability requires the following constructs, none of which exist in 1.15.1:
+
+| Construct required by the CVE | Present in libheif 1.15.1? |
+|-------------------------------|----------------------------|
+| `stts` box parsing (`Box_stts`) | **No** |
+| `Box_stts::get_sample_duration()` method | **No** |
+| Time-to-sample iteration / sample-duration lookup | **No** |
+
+Because 1.15.1 has no track-reading subsystem, the `stts` box is an **unrecognized box**
+and is skipped by its declared size during parsing. There is no loop to enter, so the
+"infinite loop during file open" cannot happen.
+
+---
+
+## 4. Source verification
+
+Run against the bookworm 1.15.1 source tree:
+
+```text
+$ grep -rn "Box_stts\|get_sample_duration" --include=*.cc --include=*.h libheif/
+(no matches — grep exit status 1)
+```
+
+Both symbols named by the CVE are absent. The same subsystem-level confirmation documented
+for CVE-2026-32738 (Section 4 above) applies: the `stts` box is not among the still-image
+`Box_*` classes defined in `libheif/box.h`, and the entire `moov`/`trak`/`stbl` hierarchy
+is missing.
+
+---
+
+## 5. Recommended triage entry
+
+```
+[bookworm] - libheif <not-affected> (Image-sequence/track parsing — Box_stts —
+was introduced after 1.15.1; bookworm predates the feature)
+```
+
+---
+
+## 6. Scope and caveats
+
+- This analysis is verified against the **upstream libheif 1.15.1** tree, which matches
+  the version Debian bookworm ships.
+- Debian does **not** backport new *features* (such as the image-sequence/track reading
+  API) into stable point releases; it backports security and bug fixes only. Therefore the
+  vulnerable code will not be present in the Debian source package (`.dsc`) either.
+- If a fully airtight confirmation is required, the same `grep` check above can be re-run
+  against the unpacked bookworm source package — the expected result is zero matches.
+
+---
+
+*Verdict: CVE-2026-32739 is a **false positive for Debian bookworm (libheif 1.15.1)** —
+the affected code (`Box_stts::get_sample_duration()`) does not exist in the shipped
+version.*
