+
+# CVE-2026-32741 — False Positive for Debian 12 (Bookworm)
+
+| Field | Value |
+|--------|--------|
+| **CVE ID** | CVE-2026-32741 |
+| **Component** | libheif |
+| **Distribution** | Debian 12 (Bookworm) |
+| **Bookworm package** | `libheif` source package, version `1.15.1-1` (and security/point-release respins on the 1.15.1 base) |
+| **Upstream affected** | libheif ≤ 1.21.2 *that ship `MaskImageCodec::decode_mask_image()`* (introduced in 1.17.0) |
+| **Upstream fixed in** | libheif 1.22.0 (commit `12369427`) |
+| **Assessment** | **FALSE POSITIVE for Bookworm — package is not vulnerable, no patch required.** |
+
+---
+
+## 1. Why this CVE is being flagged
+
+Scanners (Trivy, Grype, OSV-Scanner, Anchore, etc.) match this CVE against any package whose version compares as `<= 1.21.2`. The Bookworm package version `1.15.1-1` satisfies that comparison, so scanners flag it.
+
+However, **version comparison alone is incorrect here**. The CVE describes a defect in a specific function — `MaskImageCodec::decode_mask_image()` — and that function does not exist in the 1.15.1 source tree shipped by Bookworm. Scanners that rely purely on the upstream advisory's "≤ 1.21.2" range generate a false match.
+
+## 2. Why Bookworm's libheif 1.15.1 is not vulnerable
+
+The CVE describes a heap buffer overflow inside:
+
+```cpp
+// libheif/image-items/mask_image.cc — DOES NOT EXIST IN 1.15.1
+Error MaskImageCodec::decode_mask_image(...) {
+    ...
+    if (((uint32_t)stride) == width) {
+        memcpy(dst, data.data(), data.size());   // <-- overflow
+    }
+    ...
+}
+```
+
+For this bug to be reachable, **all of the following must be true** in the deployed source:
+
+1. The `MaskImageCodec` class exists.
+2. `MaskImageCodec::decode_mask_image()` exists and is dispatched for items of fourcc type `mski`.
+3. The decoder reads `mskC` (mask configuration) and `ispe` (image spatial extent) properties.
+4. There is a single-`memcpy` fast-path branch sized by `data.size()` (attacker-controlled).
+
+In libheif 1.15.1 **none of those preconditions are met**. The entire HEIF "mask image" (`mski`) feature was not present yet.
+
+### 2.1 Direct evidence — the file does not exist
+
+```bash
+$ git ls-tree -r v1.15.1 --name-only | grep -i mask
+(empty — no results)
+```
+
+```bash
+$ git grep -nE "MaskImage|decode_mask|mskC|fourcc\\(\"mski\"\\)" v1.15.1 -- '*.cc' '*.h'
+(empty — no results)
+```
+
+There is no `mask_image.cc`, no `mask_image.h`, no `MaskImageCodec` symbol, no `mski` fourcc handler, and no `mskC` property parser anywhere in the Bookworm source.
+
+### 2.2 Upstream history — when the vulnerable code actually landed
+
+| Upstream Commit | Description | First Tagged Release |
+|-----------------|-------------|----------------------|
+| `94f9a09e` | Created `libheif/codecs/mask_image.{cc,h}` and `MaskImageCodec::decode_mask_image()` | **1.17.0** |
+| `b6a77bff` | Added the inline `if (stride == width) memcpy(dst, data.data(), data.size())` fast path | **1.19.0** |
+| `e127d201` | Moved codecs into `libheif/image-items/` (the path referenced in the CVE patch) | Post-1.17 refactor |
+| `12369427` | CVE-2026-32741 fix | **1.22.0** |
+
+Bookworm shipped from the 1.15.1 base, which predates `94f9a09e` by two minor releases. The vulnerable function literally did not exist when 1.15.1 was tagged.
+
+### 2.3 Runtime behaviour with a malicious `mski` file
+
+When libheif 1.15.1 encounters a HEIF container whose primary item or a referenced item has fourcc `mski`:
+
+- `HeifContext::interpret_heif_file()` does not recognise the item type as a decodable image and either returns an `heif_error_Unsupported_feature` error or silently ignores the reference.
+- No `memcpy` of attacker-controlled length occurs because the vulnerable code path has not yet been implemented.
+
+A crafted proof-of-concept HEIF that triggers the overflow on affected versions will simply fail to decode on Bookworm's 1.15.1 release.
+
+## 3. How to verify locally
+
+```bash
+# Confirm the package version
+$ dpkg-query -W -f='${Version}\n' libheif1
+1.15.1-1
+
+# Confirm the source has no mask-image codec
+$ apt-get source libheif
+$ cd libheif-1.15.1
+
+$ find . -iname '*mask*'
+# no results
+
+$ grep -RE "MaskImage|decode_mask|mskC" .
+# no results
+
+$ grep -RE 'fourcc\("mski"\)' .
+# no results
+```
+
+If all three searches return no matches, the vulnerable code path is absent from the source and the package is not affected.
+
+## 4. Recommended action
+
+### Do not patch
+
+There is nothing to patch because the vulnerable function does not exist in the Bookworm source tree.
+
+### Mark as not affected
+
+Suggested metadata:
+
+```yaml
+status: not_affected
+justification: vulnerable_code_not_present
+impact_statement: >
+  libheif 1.15.1 (Bookworm) predates the introduction of HEIF mask-image
+  (mski) decoding. The vulnerable function
+  MaskImageCodec::decode_mask_image() was first added in upstream 1.17.0,
+  and the specific memcpy fast path was introduced in 1.19.0.
+  Neither exists in this version, making the reported heap buffer overflow
+  unreachable.
+```
+
+### Example VEX / OpenVEX statement
+
+```json
+{
+  "vulnerability": "CVE-2026-32741",
+  "products": [
+    "pkg:deb/debian/libheif@1.15.1-1?distro=bookworm"
+  ],
+  "status": "not_affected",
+  "justification": "vulnerable_code_not_present"
+}
+```
+
+For Trivy, this can also be expressed using a `.trivyignore` entry with a justification comment, though a VEX document is preferred because it is machine-readable and portable across scanners.
+
+## 5. References
+
+- Upstream fix commit: https://github.com/strukturag/libheif/commit/123694271ac02f2de68a3ccdc5d483eb8a2ae593
+- Upstream introduction of `MaskImageCodec`: commit `94f9a09e` (released in 1.17.0)
+- Upstream introduction of the vulnerable memcpy fast path: commit `b6a77bff` (released in 1.19.0)
+- Debian Bookworm package: https://packages.debian.org/bookworm/libheif1
+
+## Conclusion
+
+**CVE-2026-32741 is a false positive for Debian 12 (Bookworm).** Although scanners flag `libheif` 1.15.1 based on a broad version range, the vulnerable `MaskImageCodec::decode_mask_image()` implementation and associated `mski` decoding support were introduced only in later upstream releases. Since the vulnerable code does not exist in Bookworm's source tree, the package should be classified as **not affected** with the justification **`vulnerable_code_not_present`**.
