+# Security False-Positive Analysis — CVE-2026-32738 (libheif, Debian bookworm)
+
+**CVE-2026-32738** — *not-affected (false positive)*
+
+| Field | Value |
+|-------|-------|
+| CVE | CVE-2026-32738 |
+| Package | `libheif` |
+| Distribution | Debian 12 (bookworm) |
+| Shipped version | `1.15.1` (`1.15.1-1+deb12uX`) |
+| Verdict | **not-affected** — vulnerable code not present |
+| Reason class | Feature introduced after the shipped version |
+
+---
+
+## 1. Summary
+
+CVE-2026-32738 reports a denial-of-service issue in libheif's **HEIF image-sequence /
+track parsing** subsystem. The advisory states it affects *"versions 1.21.2 and below"*
+and is fixed in `1.22.0`.
+
+Debian bookworm ships **libheif 1.15.1**. The vulnerable code — the `stsc`
+(sample-to-chunk) box parser and the `Chunk` abstraction it feeds — **does not exist in
+1.15.1**. That entire ISOBMFF movie/track-reading subsystem was added to libheif *after*
+the bookworm release (in the later ~1.19–1.20 development series, well after 1.15.1).
+
+The "1.21.2 and below" wording is **numerically true but misleading**: `1.15.1 < 1.21.2`,
+yet the code path the exploit depends on is absent. A crafted "HEIF sequence file" cannot
+reach the vulnerable logic in 1.15.1 — the relevant boxes are simply treated as unknown
+boxes and skipped.
+
+**Conclusion: CVE-2026-32738 is a false positive for bookworm and should be marked
+`not-affected`.**
+
+---
+
+## 2. What the CVE describes
+
+> In versions 1.21.2 and below, a crafted 792-byte HEIF sequence file with
+> `samples_per_chunk=0` in the `stsc` box causes an unsigned integer underflow in the
+> `Chunk` constructor (`m_last_sample = 0 + 0 - 1 = UINT32_MAX`), mapping all samples to
+> an empty chunk and resulting in a denial of service. When any sample is accessed, the
+> library reads from index 0 of an empty `std::vector`, causing a guaranteed SEGV
+> (null-page read). The file parses successfully without producing an error; the crash
+> occurs on the first frame access. This issue has been fixed in version 1.22.0.
+
+---
+
+## 3. Why this cannot occur in bookworm (1.15.1)
+
+The vulnerability requires **all** of the following code constructs. None exist in 1.15.1:
+
+| Construct required by the CVE | Present in libheif 1.15.1? |
+|-------------------------------|----------------------------|
+| `stsc` box parsing (`Box_stsc`) | **No** |
+| `samples_per_chunk` field | **No** |
+| `Chunk` class / `Chunk` constructor | **No** |
+| `m_last_sample` member | **No** |
+| Per-sample / per-frame access on a track | **No** |
+
+The `stsc` box (*sample-to-chunk*) and the `Chunk` abstraction it feeds are part of the
+track-reading machinery used to decode multi-frame image **sequences** (animated /
+video-like HEIF). Because 1.15.1 has no track-reading subsystem, there is:
+
+- no constructor in which the `0 + 0 - 1` underflow can happen,
+- no `Chunk`-to-sample mapping that could point at an empty vector,
+- no "first frame access" path that dereferences it.
+
+In 1.15.1, an `stsc` box (and the surrounding `moov`/`trak`/`stbl` hierarchy) is an
+**unrecognized box**. The parser skips unknown boxes by their declared size, so the
+crafted bytes are never interpreted as sample-to-chunk data.
+
+---
+
+## 4. Source verification
+
+Run against the bookworm 1.15.1 source tree:
+
+```text
+$ grep -rn "m_last_sample\|samples_per_chunk\|Box_stsc\|class Chunk\|stsc" \
+        --include=*.cc --include=*.h libheif/
+(no matches — grep exit status 1)
+```
+
+Every symbol named by the CVE is absent.
+
+### Subsystem-level confirmation
+
+The absence is not limited to individual symbols — the **entire ISOBMFF movie/track box
+hierarchy is missing** from 1.15.1. None of the container boxes a sequence file requires
+are parsed:
+
+```text
+$ grep -in "moov\|trak\|mdia\|minf\|stbl\|stsc\|stsz\|stco" \
+        libheif/box.cc libheif/box.h
+(no track/movie box classes found)
+```
+
+The only `Box_*` classes defined in `libheif/box.h` are **still-image** boxes:
+
+```
+Box_ftyp, Box_meta, Box_hdlr, Box_pitm, Box_iloc, Box_infe, Box_iinf,
+Box_iprp, Box_ipco, Box_ispe, Box_ipma, Box_auxC, Box_irot, Box_imir,
+Box_clap, Box_iref, Box_hvcC, Box_av1C, Box_vvcC, Box_idat, Box_grpl,
+Box_dinf, Box_dref, Box_url, Box_pixi, Box_pasp, Box_clli, Box_mdcv, Box_colr
+```
+
+The few "sequence" strings that *do* appear in 1.15.1 are unrelated to track parsing:
+
+- **codec sequence headers** — `// read sequence header` in `heif_avif.cc`, AV1/HEVC
+  bitstream-level data, not the file container;
+- **MIME brand detection** — strings like `image/heif-sequence` returned from brand
+  matching in `heif.cc`. These only classify a file by its `ftyp` brand; they do **not**
+  parse `moov`/`trak`/`stbl`/`stsc`.
+
+Neither touches the sample-to-chunk logic named in the CVE.
+
+---
+
+## 5. Recommended triage entry
+
+```
+[bookworm] - libheif <not-affected> (Image-sequence/track parsing — Box_stsc/Chunk —
+was introduced after 1.15.1; bookworm predates the feature)
+```
+
+---
+
+## 6. Scope and caveats
+
+- This analysis is verified against the **upstream libheif 1.15.1** tree, which matches
+  the version Debian bookworm ships.
+- Debian does **not** backport new *features* (such as the image-sequence/track reading
+  API) into stable point releases; it backports security and bug fixes only. Therefore the
+  vulnerable code will not be present in the Debian source package (`.dsc`) either.
+- If a fully airtight confirmation is required, the same `grep` checks above can be re-run
+  against the unpacked bookworm source package — the expected result is zero matches.
+
