+**CVE-2026-32741 is a false positive for Debian 12 (Bookworm).** Although scanners flag `libheif` 1.15.1 based on a broad version range, the vulnerable `MaskImageCodec::decode_mask_image()` implementation and associated `mski` decoding support were introduced only in later upstream releases. Since the vulnerable code does not exist in Bookworm's source tree, the package should be classified as **not affected** with the justification **`vulnerable_code_not_present`**.
+
+## CVE-2026-41071 — False Positive for Debian 12 (Bookworm)
+
+| Field                 | Value                                                                                                                 |
+| --------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
+| **CVE ID**            | CVE-2026-41071                                                                                                        |
+| **Component**         | libheif                                                                                                               |
+| **CWE**               | CWE-125: Out-of-bounds Read (heap-buffer-overflow)                                                                    |
+| **Distribution**      | Debian 12 (Bookworm)                                                                                                  |
+| **Bookworm package**  | `libheif` source package, version `1.15.1-1` / `1.15.1-1+deb12u1` (security/point-release respins on the 1.15.1 base) |
+| **Upstream affected** | libheif ≤ 1.21.2 *that ship `SampleAuxInfoReader` / the sequences-track subsystem* (introduced in 1.20.0)             |
+| **Upstream fixed in** | libheif 1.22.0 (commit `f20c81745e917b4c496615140385c86d7a2fa58d`)                                                    |
+| **Assessment**        | **FALSE POSITIVE for Bookworm — package is not vulnerable, no patch required.**                                       |
+
+---
+
+### 1. Why this CVE is being flagged
+
+Scanners (Trivy, Grype, OSV-Scanner, Anchore, etc.) and the Debian security tracker match this CVE against any package whose version compares as `<= 1.21.2`. The Bookworm package version `1.15.1-1` satisfies that comparison, so it is flagged.
+
+The Debian security tracker currently lists Bookworm (`1.15.1-1+deb12u1`) as *vulnerable*, but this is the default "open" state applied automatically to every version at or below the fixed release and is not a code-level determination.
+
+**Version comparison alone is incorrect here.** The CVE describes a defect in a specific function — the `SampleAuxInfoReader` constructor in the image-sequences subsystem — and neither that function, that file, nor the entire sequences/track feature exists in the 1.15.1 source tree shipped by Bookworm. The advisory's "≤ 1.21.2" range therefore produces a false match against 1.15.1.
+
+### 2. Why Bookworm's libheif 1.15.1 is not vulnerable
+
+The CVE describes an out-of-bounds read in the construction of a `SampleAuxInfoReader`, while parsing the Sample Auxiliary Information Size (`saiz`) box of a HEIF sequence/track:
+
+```cpp
+// libheif/sequences/track.cc — DOES NOT EXIST IN 1.15.1
+SampleAuxInfoReader::SampleAuxInfoReader(...) {
+    ...
+    // iterates saiz->get_num_samples() times without checking it
+    // against the size of the chunk table; current_chunk walks past
+    // chunks.size() for a crafted file --> OOB read on `chunks`
+    assert(current_chunk < chunks.size());   // pre-fix
+    ...
+}
+```
+
+The fix (`f20c817`) adds two guards:
+
+1. A bounds check that breaks out of the loop when `current_chunk >= chunks.size()`.
+2. Validation in `Track::load()` that rejects files when `saiz->get_num_samples() > m_stsz->num_samples()`.
+
+For this bug to be reachable, **all of the following must be true**:
+
+1. The image-sequences subsystem exists.
+2. `libheif/sequences/track.cc` and the `Track` class exist.
+3. Sample Auxiliary Information (`saiz` / `saio`) parsing exists via `SampleAuxInfoReader`.
+4. A crafted file can drive `current_chunk` past `chunks.size()` because the loop trusts `saiz->get_num_samples()`.
+
+In libheif 1.15.1 **none of these conditions are met**. The entire sequences/track subsystem did not exist.
+
+#### 2.1 Direct evidence — the file and symbols do not exist
+
+```bash
+$ git ls-tree -r HEAD --name-only | grep -iE 'sequences|track\.cc|saiz|saio'
+(empty — no results)
+```
+
+```bash
+$ git grep -nE 'SampleAuxInfoReader|get_num_samples|fourcc\("saiz"\)|class Track' HEAD -- '*.cc' '*.h'
+(empty — no results)
+```
+
+There is no `libheif/sequences/` directory, no `track.cc`, no `SampleAuxInfoReader`, no `saiz`/`saio` parser, and no track or sequence decode path anywhere in the Bookworm source tree.
+
+#### 2.2 Upstream history — when the vulnerable code actually landed
+
+| Upstream milestone | What it added                                                                                                                        | First tagged release |
+| ------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | -------------------- |
+| Sequences API      | Introduced image-sequences support, track reading/writing, Sample Auxiliary Information (`saiz` / `saio`), and `SampleAuxInfoReader` | **1.20.0**           |
+| `f20c817`          | CVE-2026-41071 fix (bounds checks and validation)                                                                                    | **1.22.0**           |
+
+Bookworm shipped from the 1.15.1 base, which predates the sequences API by **five minor releases**. The vulnerable function did not exist in 1.15.1.
+
+#### 2.3 Runtime behaviour with a malicious sequence file
+
+When libheif 1.15.1 encounters a HEIF/MP4-style file containing image-sequence tracks with a malformed `saiz` box:
+
+* No sequence/track reader exists.
+* No code parses `saiz` or `saio`.
+* No `SampleAuxInfoReader` exists.
+* The vulnerable loop does not exist.
+
+A proof-of-concept file that triggers the vulnerability on 1.21.x cannot reach the vulnerable code path on Bookworm's 1.15.1 release.
+
+### 3. How to verify locally
+
+```bash
+# Confirm package version
+$ dpkg-query -W -f='${Version}\n' libheif1
+1.15.1-1
+
+# Or point release
+1.15.1-1+deb12u1
+
+# Confirm source has no sequence subsystem
+$ apt-get source libheif
+$ cd libheif-1.15.1
+
+$ find . -iname '*track*' -o -iname '*sequence*'
+# no results
+
+$ grep -RE 'SampleAuxInfoReader|fourcc\("saiz"\)' .
+# no results
+
+$ grep -RE 'class Track' .
+# no results
+```
+
+If these searches return no matches, the vulnerable code path is absent.
+
+### 4. Recommended action
+
+#### Do not patch
+
+There is nothing to patch because the vulnerable function and the entire subsystem do not exist in this source tree.
+
+#### Mark as not affected
+
+Suggested metadata:
+
+```yaml
+status: not_affected
+justification: vulnerable_code_not_present
+impact_statement: >
+  libheif 1.15.1 (Bookworm) predates the introduction of the
+  image-sequences/track subsystem and Sample Auxiliary Information
+  (saiz) parsing. The vulnerable SampleAuxInfoReader constructor was
+  introduced in upstream 1.20.0. Neither the class, the file
+  libheif/sequences/track.cc, nor any saiz decode path exists in this
+  version, making the out-of-bounds read unreachable.
+```
+
+#### Example VEX / OpenVEX statement
+
+```json
+{
+  "vulnerability": "CVE-2026-41071",
+  "products": [
+    "pkg:deb/debian/libheif@1.15.1-1?distro=bookworm"
+  ],
+  "status": "not_affected",
+  "justification": "vulnerable_code_not_present"
+}
+```
+
+For Trivy, this can also be represented using a `.trivyignore` entry with a justification comment, although a VEX document is preferred.
+
+> **Note on Debian patch series:** This assessment is based on upstream libheif 1.15.1. Debian's `1.15.1-1+deb12u1` includes a small patch series, but there is no indication that the entire 1.20.0 sequences subsystem was backported. If strict verification is required, inspect the Debian patch set and confirm that no patch introduces `libheif/sequences/` or `SampleAuxInfoReader`.
+
+### 5. References
+
+* Upstream fix commit: https://github.com/strukturag/libheif/commit/f20c81745e917b4c496615140385c86d7a2fa58d
+* Upstream introduction of the sequences API / SAI (`saiz`) handling: libheif 1.20.0 release — https://github.com/strukturag/libheif/releases/tag/v1.20.0
+* CVE record: https://vulnerability.circl.lu/vuln/cve-2026-41071
+* Debian security tracker: https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2026-41071
+* Debian Bookworm libheif package: https://packages.debian.org/bookworm/libheif1
+
+### Conclusion
+
+**CVE-2026-41071 is a false positive for Debian 12 (Bookworm).** The vulnerable `SampleAuxInfoReader` constructor and the entire image-sequences subsystem were introduced in libheif 1.20.0, while Debian Bookworm ships from the 1.15.1 code base. Since the vulnerable code does not exist in the deployed source tree, the package should be classified as **not affected** with the justification **`vulnerable_code_not_present`**.
